author: @random789-w3w
text:
let's get more specific with Vietnamese pronouns in different social situations:

Formal Situations:

Addressing Someone:

Ông/Bà + Last Name: This is the most formal way to address someone, especially someone older or in a position of authority. (Ông for men, Bà for women)
Chức Vụ (Title) + Last Name: You can also use their title followed by their last name, like Giám Đốc Nguyễn (Director Nguyen).
Anh/Chị + Last Name: This is a more polite way to address someone you don't know well but is still your age or younger.
Referring to Yourself:

Tôi: This is the standard pronoun for "I" in formal situations.
Referring to Others:

Ông ấy/Bà ấy (he/she): These are formal pronouns for the third person.
Ông/Bà + Last Name: You can also use their title and last name again.
Họ (they): This is the formal pronoun for "they."
Informal Situations (Friends/Family):

Addressing Someone:

Tên (Name): You can directly call someone by their name, especially close friends.
Anh/Chị (older sibling): Used for friends or acquaintances slightly older than you.
Em (younger sibling): Used for friends or acquaintances younger than you.
Bạn: This is the casual way to say "you" with friends.
Kinship terms: You can use kinship terms like chú (uncle), cô (aunt), or anh họ (male cousin) for close friends, even if they aren't actually related.
Referring to Yourself:

Tao/Tớ: These are informal pronouns for "I" used only with very close friends.
Referring to Others:

Anh ấy/Chị ấy (he/she): Can be used informally as well.
Bạn ấy (he/she): This is a casual way to refer to someone (friend) in the third person.
Em ấy (he/she): Used for a younger friend in the third person.
Họ (they): Still used for "they" in informal situations.
Tên (name): You can also use their name to refer to them in the third person with friends.
Remember:

It's always better to err on the side of caution and use more formal language when unsure.
The specific pronoun choices can also vary depending on regional dialects.
